Quick little tip for those trying to improve the dread “rhythm kicks” 
.
1. Sync up the upper body and lower body 
2. Breath out on the kick and in on the rest
3. Make sure you are balanced and NOT over rotating. 
.

Posting this only because the new year is around the corner…. A LOT of trainers are going to try and sale you a bullshit workout routine. 
.
I get DMS every day asking about “what I do” 
.
The secret is consistency and intensity. The workout only works when you work. 
.
I make sure to push myself and understand my body has a cycle. As a Athlete I will see outward  changes depending on the programming and intake in food etc. 
.
Make a choice to make a change and know your goals. 
.

Here’s a quick little exercise you can do using a balance disk. 
.
.
1. Make sure you are pressing into the ball of your foot..this helps your hips drive your power into the kick. 
.
2. Makes sure the kicking leg explodes off the ground “heel to toe explode” 
.

@muaythaitips of the day 
Posted this a few months ago after a training session with @jonattawut 
.
Those that know jo know he’s extremely helpful,humble, and encouraging in the best way 
.
He’s also can completely wreck most of the human race in a fight! 
.
His approach to training is drastically different then most fighters I know. He takes time to invest in his training partners and those around him. 
. 
I asked jo his secret to a solid defense and his response was “be good at holding pads” 
.
I’ve said this for years and I know this echos with so many other great coaches around the world. 
.
The biggest thing most fighters miss this day and age is giving back and investing into the community. I’ve seen and heard fighters say “I’m not helping this ______”  or “get someone else to hold for them” 
.
If you want to go to the next level In fighting I truly believe it starts with being a good pad holder. It’s the greatest return of investment you can get. 
.
